<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-342-802  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 342 802.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  June 12 1989 v8 n12 p3(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Court will decide if agencies must pay back judgement fund. (USCourt of Appeals for the Federal Circuit)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Power, Kevin.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>A decision is expected in the fall of 1989 from the US Court ofAppeals for the Federal Circuit on whether or not agencies mustreimburse the US Treasury Department for payments to vendors thatsuccessfully protest automatic data processing procurements.andP;  TheJustice Department is appealing a General Services AdministrationBoard of Contract Appeals (GSBCA) decision requiring the US Armyto repay the permanent indefinite judgement fund for a sum awardedto a protester.andP;  Justice says the Competition in Contracting Actdoes not require agencies to reimburse the fund.andP;  Justice alsoclaims GSBCA has violated Article 1 of the Constitution,prohibiting appropriations from the Treasury without Congressionalauthorization.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Law SuitUnited States. Department of JusticeUnited States. Department of the TreasuryGovernment ContractsGovernment RegulationUnited States. General Services Administration. Board of ContractAppeals.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Court Will Decide If Agencies Must Pay Back Judgment FundandM;The U.S.andP;  court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit is expected to rule thisfall on whether agencies are required to reimburse the Treasury for paymentsto vendors that successfully protest ADP procurements.andM;The Justice Department is appealing a recent decision by the General ServicesAdministration Board of Contract Appeals that required the Army to repay thepermanent indefinite judgment fund for a sum awarded to a protestor, JulieResearch Laboratories Inc. of New York.andP;  Justice attorneys contend theCompetition in Contracting Act (CICA) does not require agencies to reimbursethe fund and the GSBCA has no authority to order pay-backs.andM;The fund was established in 1956 to provide the government with a permanentappropriation for settling claims of up to $100,000 without congressionalapproval.andP;  Before that Congress had to approve all such paymentsindividually, and often claims were not paid until annual budget legislationwas passed.andM;The fund is administered by the General Accounting Office.andM;Congress made the fund &quot;indefinite&quot; in 1977 when it removed the payment cap,and in 1978 it incorporated the fund into the contract disputes process toensure that the government could settle its contract claims promptly.andM;But in the Julie Labs case, GSBCA Judge Vincent LaBella ordered the Army toreimburse the fund for the $20,986.13 paid out to Julie.andP;  LaBella said thatbecause a protest award is &quot;inextricably connected with the true economiccosts of the procurement, it is appropriate that the fund be reimbursed bythe agency whose appropriations were used for the contract out of availablefunds or by obtaining additional appropriations for such purposes.&quot;andM;In briefs filed with the appeals court, Justice said Congress did not requirereimbursement under CICA and therefore the GSBCA exceeded its statutoryauthority to grant relief.andM;The department claimed the GSBCA also violated Article 1 of the Constitution,which prohibits appropriations from the Treasury without congressionalauthorization.andM;Cyrus Phillips, an attorney in the Washington office of McGuire, Woods,Battle andamp; Boothe, representing Julie Labs in theappeals case, said orderingreimbursements in consistent with Congress' original intent in CICA.andM;Phillips, a former GSBCA judge, said although reimbursement is not spelledout in the Brooks Act, GSBCA can use its contract disputes procedures toassure that acquisitions costs are paid by the contracting agencies ratherthan hidden in payments from the fund.andM;&quot;An omission of explicit language in a statute is meaningless for purposes ofstatutory interpretation where the explicit language supposedly omitted isunnecessary.&quot; Phillips said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>